ca 1213","1194":"1194","murom, Vladimirskaya Oblast', Rússia":"murom, Vladimirskaya Oblast', Rusland"},"en":{"Abt 1196–":"about 1196–Deceased","1194–1237":"1194–1237","1214–1248":"1214–1248","1196–Female":"1196–Deceased","Abt 1196":"about 1196","1248":"1248","1237":"1237","1214":"1214","Abt 1214":"about 1214","1196":"1196","Abt 1213":"about 1213","1194":"1194","murom, Vladimirskaya Oblast', Rússia":"murom, Vladimir Oblast, Russia","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Murom","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Manuel, Jose, Jesus, Juan, Miguel, Alejandro, Arturo, Francisco, Luis, Ruben, Margarita, Alfonso.  Portuguese Armanda.  Italian Antonio, Angelo, Pasquale, Rocco, Salvatore, Carmelo, Carmine, Cira, Filomena, Heriberto, Luigi, Mirella.","Spanish and Italian: habitational name from any of various places in Spain and Italy named Muro, from <i>muro</i> ‘wall’. Compare Spanish   Del Muro   and Italian   De Muro  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Del Muro","meanings":["Spanish: variant, with the preposition and definite article <i>del</i> ‘from the’, of   Muro  . This surname is very rare in Spain; it is found mainly in Mexico."]}]},{"name":"Yurij","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["The usual Russian form of   George  , also used occasionally in the English-speaking world."],"variants":[{"name":"George","meanings":["Via Old French and Latin, from Greek <i>Georgios</i> (a derivative of <i>geōrgos</i> ‘farmer’, from <i>gē</i> ‘earth’ + <i>ergein</i> ‘to work’). This was the name of several early saints, including the shadowy figure who is now the patron of England (as well as of Germany and Portugal). If the saint existed at all, he was perhaps martyred in Palestine in the persecutions of Christians instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  at the beginning of the 4th century. The popular legend in which the hero slays a dragon is a medieval Italian invention. He was for a long time a more important saint in the Orthodox Church than in the West, and the name was not much used in England during the Middle Ages, even after  St George  came to be regarded as the patron of England in the 14th century. Its use increased from the 1400s, and by  1500  it was regularly among the most popular male names. This popularity was reinforced when  George I  came to the throne in  1714 , bringing this name with him from Germany. It has been one of the most popular English boys' names ever since."]},{"name":"Georgi","meanings":["From Greek <i>Georgios</i>.  See  <b>George</b>   ."]}]},{"name":"Davidovich","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Jewish Rina, Avi, Izya, Mendel, Rifka, Rivka, Tuvia.  Russian Boris, Svetlana, Arkadiy, Ayzik, Fima, Losif, Yuriy.","Ukrainian (standard transliteration <b>Davydovych</b>), Belorussian, and Jewish (eastern Ashkenazic): patronymic from the personal name   David   (Ukrainian <i>Davyd</i>).","Americanized form of Serbian and Croatian <b>Davidović</b>, a cognate of 1 above."],"variants":[{"name":"David","meanings":["Biblical name, borne by the greatest of all the kings of Israel, whose history is recounted with great vividness in the first and second books of Samuel and elsewhere. As a boy he killed the giant Philistine Goliath with his slingshot. As king of Judah, and later of all Israel, he expanded the power of the Israelites and established the security of their kingdom. He was also noted as a poet, many of the Psalms being attributed to him. The Hebrew derivation of the name is uncertain; it is said by some to represent a nursery word meaning ‘darling’. It is a very popular Jewish name, but is almost equally common among Gentiles in the English-speaking world. It is particularly common in Wales and Scotland, having been borne by the patron saint of Wales (  see  Dewi   ) and by two medieval kings of Scotland."]}]},{"name":"Of","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of   Oswald   or any of the various other names beginning with <i>Os-</i>."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Mrs- Yurij Davidovich Duchess Of Murom was born about 1196. She married Yurij Davidovich Duke Murom about 1213, in murom, Vladimir Oblast, Russia. They were the parents of at least 1 son."},"et":{"Abt 1196–":"umbes 1196–Surnud","1194–1237":"1194–1237","1214–1248":"1214–1248","1196–Female":"1196–Surnud","Abt 1196":"umbes 1196","1248":"1248","1237":"1237","1214":"1214","Abt 1214":"umbes 1214","1196":"1196","Abt 1213":"umbes 1213","1194":"1194","murom, Vladimirskaya Oblast', Rússia":"murom, Vladimirskaya Oblast', Venemaa"},"fi":{"Abt 1196–":"noin 1196–Kuollut","1194–1237":"1194–1237","1214–1248":"1214–1248","1196–Female":"1196–Kuollut","Abt 1196":"noin 1196","1248":"1248","1237":"1237","1214":"1214","Abt 1214":"noin 1214","1196":"1196","Abt 1213":"noin 1213","1194":"1194","murom, Vladimirskaya Oblast', Rússia":"murom, Vladimirskaya Oblast', Venäjä"},"fr":{"Abt 1196–":"environ 1196–Décédée","1194–1237":"1194–1237","1214–1248":"1214–1248","1196–Female":"1196–Décédée","Abt 1196":"environ 1196","1248":"1248","1237":"1237","1214":"1214","Abt 1214":"environ 1214","1196":"1196","Abt 1213":"environ 1213","1194":"1194","murom, Vladimirskaya Oblast', Rússia":"murom, Vladimirskaya Oblast', Russie","lifeSummary":"Mrs- Yurij Davidovich Duchess Of Murom est née environ 1196. Elle a épousé Yurij Davidovich Duke Murom environ 1213, à murom, Vladimirskaya Oblast', Russie. Ils ont eu au moins 1 fils."},"de":{"Abt 1196–":"um 1196–Verstorben","1194–1237":"1194–1237","1214–1248":"1214–1248","1196–Female":"1196–Verstorben","Abt 1196":"um 1196","1248":"1248","1237":"1237","1214":"1214","Abt 1214":"um 1214","1196":"1196","Abt 1213":"um 1213","1194":"1194","murom, Vlad